Packages

Throughout the course we will be using a standard suite of packages. The top of any R Notebook you produce for this course should have the following code. This will typically be provided to you, and you should not have a need to alter it.

library(car)       # special functions for summarizing models
library(tidyverse) # plotting and data manipulation
library(stringr)   # working with character strings
library(broom)     # making model output pretty
source(str_c("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/reyesem/",
             "MA223-Additional-Files/master/BootstrapFunctions.R")) # bootstrap

Data Manipulation

Data is rarely perfect when we first obtain it. Often times, we will need to make changes. There are a few tasks which are performed regularly:

  • mutate(): manipulate variables or make transformations.
  • arrange(): order (sort) the data according to specific variables.
  • filter(): filter the dataset to retain only a specified subset.

As an example, while the US measures fuel efficiency in miles per gallon, other countries often report the gallons required for a single mile. This new variable Gallons_per_Mile can be created using manipulate():

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(Gallons_per_Mile = 1/mpg)

Notice that we use the pipe operator (%>%) here; this essentially says take the dataset mtcars and feed it into the manipulate() function. The remainder of the function has a New_Variable = transformation feel to it. The entire result is stored in the dataset that we started with, essentially overwriting the original dataset. The result is shown below:

If we only want to consider automatic transmissions, and perhaps save those in a separate dataset, we can use filter():

automatic.only <- mtcars %>%
  filter(am == 0)

When making comparisons, == is asking “are you equal?” We keep the “yes/true” statements. The original mtcars dataset is not altered; it remains unchanged. Instead, we have taken it, filtered it down, and then stored the results in automatic.only (shown below).

When we work with categorical variables, we often want to keep the values (or group labels) as something very readable. In order to do this, we may need to recode what is there. Consider the variable am (transmission type). It is currently a 0/1 variable, which is not extremely clear that 1 represents manual transmission. We alter this using mutate().

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(am = recode(am, 
                     `0` = "automatic",
                     `1` = "manual"))

Numerical Summaries

If you want to preserve the output of the dataset, we can use the summarise() function.

mtcars %>%
  summarise(Mean_MPG = mean(mpg),
            Pct_manual = mean(am=="manual"))
##   Mean_MPG Pct_manual
## 1 20.09062    0.40625

What is nice about the summarise() function is that it works well after grouping the dataset. The following code breaks the dataset into groups based on the number of cylinders and then computes the summaries.

mtcars %>%
  group_by(cyl) %>%
  summarise(Mean_MPG = mean(mpg),
            Pct_manual = mean(am=="manual"))
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##     cyl Mean_MPG Pct_manual
##   <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1     4 26.66364  0.7272727
## 2     6 19.74286  0.4285714
## 3     8 15.10000  0.1428571

Graphics

When examining the distribution of a categorical variable, we will primarily use a bar chart. The variable you want to summarize goes on the x-axis; you must also specify the data and it is safe to say geom = "bar" to specify a bar chart (though this is typically the default). Labels can also be passed using xlab = and ylab =. There is not much customization here; you need to use ggplot() to get more custom graphics, but that is beyond the scope of what I will expect.

qplot(x = am,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "bar",
      xlab = "Transmission Type",
      ylab = "Frequency")

If you have multiple categorical variables, consider using additional aesthetics. All categorical variables need to either be “factors” or “character strings” (wrapped in quotations ""). If they are entered as numbers, R will not know how to treat them. For example, if we want a bar chart comparing transmission types for cars with varying number of cylinders, we can ust the following code.

# Recode the number of cylinders
#  The factor() function turns the variable into a categorical one
mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(cyl = factor(cyl))

qplot(x = cyl,
      fill = am,
      data = mtcars,
      xlab = "Number of Cylinders",
      ylab = "Frequency")

The above also illustrates the importance of nice naming conventions so that the label on the legend is appropriate. Labels can be added easily with the labs() function, but past this, we will not do much customization.

qplot(x = cyl,
      fill = am,
      data = mtcars) +
  labs(x = "Number of Cylinders",
       y = "Frequency",
       fill = "Transmission")

When looking at the distribution of a single variable, we might use a histogram or a density plot. The histogram requires that you carefully specify the width of each bin. The density plot is a smoothed version of the histogram but will not work well without a sufficiently large amount of data. For each, specify the variable to be placed along the x-axis and then the type of plot is governed by geom = "plot-type".

qplot(x = mpg,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "histogram",
      binwidth = 1,
      xlab = "Miles per Gallon",
      ylab = "Frequency")

qplot(x = mpg,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "density",
      xlab = "Miles per Gallon",
      ylab = "Density")

If we are comparing a quantitative variable across levels of a categorical variable, we can consider side-by-side boxplots or violin plots.

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = am,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "boxplot",
      xlab = "Transmission Type",
      ylab = "Miles per Gallon")

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = am,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "violin",
      xlab = "Transmission Type",
      ylab = "Miles per Gallon")

We can also add additional aesthetics to make more comparisons.

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = am,
      fill = cyl,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "boxplot") +
  labs(x = "Transmission Type",
       y = "Miles per Gallon",
       fill = "Number of Cylinders")

When examining the relationship between two quantitative variables, we can use a scatterplot.

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      data = mtcars,
      ylab = "Miles per Gallon",
      xlab = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
      geom = "point")

Again, we can add more to this using additional aesthetics.

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      color = cyl,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       y = "Miles per Gallon",
       color = "Number of Cylinders")

If we are clever about layering aspects of a graphic, we can also include a smoothing line.

qplot(y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      color = cyl,
      data = mtcars,
      geom = c("point", "smooth"),
      se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       y = "Miles per Gallon",
       color = "Number of Cylinders")

Models

We primarily work with two types of models in the course: ANOVA and regression models. Due to their connection, they are fit the same way. We simply examine the output differently. All models are specified with the response ~ predictors syntax using the lm() function.

An ANOVA model examining fuel efficiency across transmission types could be examined by

anova.fit <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)
Anova(anova.fit)
## Anova Table (Type II tests)
##

A linear model examining fuel efficiency and weight would be

simple.fit <- lm(mpg ~ wt, data = mtcars)
tidy(simple.fit)
##          term  estimate std.error statistic      p.value
## 1 (Intercept) 37.285126  1.877627 19.857575 8.241799e-19
## 2          wt -5.344472  0.559101 -9.559044 1.293959e-10

A more complex linear model comes from adding additional terms using a + sign, and interactions specified using a :.

multiple.fit <- lm(mpg ~ wt + am + wt:am, data = mtcars)
tidy(multiple.fit)

Diagnostic Plots

The two diagnostic plots that may not be obvious given what we have discussed so far is a time-series plot of the residuals and a probability plot of the residuals. The time-series plot is constructed by layering components.

qplot(x = seq_along(.resid),
      y = .resid,
      data = mtcars.aug,
      geom = c("line", "point"),
      xlab = "Order of Observations",
      ylab = "Residuals")

The probability plot is created using the following

qplot(sample = .resid,
      data = mtcars.aug,
      xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles",
      ylab = "Sample Quantiles",
      geom = "qq")

A plot of the residuals against the fitted values would be given by

qplot(x = .fitted,
      y = .resid,
      data = mtcars.aug,
      xlab = "Fitted Values",
      ylab = "Residuals")

Bootstrapping

The most computational aspect of the course is bootstrapping a dataset to build an empirical model or to construct a null distribution. We will use the boot_model() function for bootstrapping. There are a couple of big things we need to think about with this function:

  • orig.model: this is the model we are fitting and for which we either want to construct confidence intervals or a p-value.
  • null.model: this is only important if you are looking at a particular p-value. This is the model which you would fit if the null model were true. Note that you have to bootstrap one p-value at a time.
  • constant.var: an indicator of whether you want to assume constant variance (default = TRUE).
  • conf.level: if you are making confidence intervals, the confidence level you want to use.

As an example, suppose we would like to compute 95% confidence intervals for the parameters of the following model: \[(\text{MPG})_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 (\text{Weight})_i + \beta_2 (\text{Manual Transmission})_i + \epsilon_i\]

This can be done with the following code

# Original Fit
original.fit <- lm(mpg ~ wt + am, data = mtcars)

# Bootstrap
#  Remember to set seed to be repeatable.
set.seed(123)
boot.ci.distn <- boot_model(original.fit, conf.level = 95, constant.var = TRUE)

# Look at Results
boot.ci.distn

In addition to simply printing the results, we can also examine the entire distribution, but we need to be careful to do this for a particular estimate (say, the parameter for weight).

plot.dat <- boot.ci.distn %>%
  filter(term=="wt")

qplot(x = estimate,
      data = plot.dat,
      geom = "density",
      xlab = "Slope for Weight",
      ylab = "Density")

If we want to construct a p-value for the hypotheses \[H_0: \beta_2 = 0 \quad \text{vs.} \quad H_1: \beta_2 \neq 0\]

testing whether the fuel efficiency is related to the manual transmission after accounting for the weight of the vehicle. In order to do this, we need to think about what the reduced model implies — namely, that the only predictor in the model is weight. The following code fits the original model, the reduced model and then bootstraps to compute the p-value. Suppose further we are not willing to make the constant variance assumption.

# Original Fit
original.fit <- lm(mpg ~ wt + am, data = mtcars)

# Null Model
reduced.fit <- lm(mpg ~ wt, data = mtcars)

# Bootstrap
set.seed(123)
boot.p.distn <- boot_model(original.fit,
                           null.model = reduced.fit,
                           constant.var = FALSE)

boot.p.distn

Using the results, we can actually examine the entire null distribution, if desired.

qplot(x = statistic,
      data = boot.p.distn,
      geom = "density",
      xlab = "Test Statistics for Transmission Under Null",
      ylab = "Null Density")
